5️⃣ Service layer (optional but keeps controllers thin)
Create a service package and a class per entity, e.g.:

package com.promineotech.musiclibrary.service;

import com.promineotech.musiclibrary.entity.Artist;
import com.promineotech.musiclibrary.repository.ArtistRepository;
import lombok.RequiredArgsConstructor;
import org.springframework.stereotype.Service;

import java.util.List;

@Service
@RequiredArgsConstructor
public class ArtistService {

    private final ArtistRepository repo;

    public List<Artist> findAll()            => repo.findAll();
    public Artist   findById(Long id)        => repo.findById(id).orElseThrow(() -> new RuntimeException("Not found"));
    public Artist   create(Artist a)         => repo.save(a);
    public Artist   update(Long id, Artist a){
        Artist existing = findById(id);
        existing.setName(a.getName());
        existing.setDescription(a.getDescription());
        return repo.save(existing);
    }
    public void     delete(Long id)          => repo.deleteById(id);
}
Copy
Repeat similar services for Album and Genre.
For the many‑to‑many part you’ll add two extra service methods:

public Album addGenre(Long albumId, Long genreId) {
    Album album = albumRepo.findById(albumId).orElseThrow(...);
    Genre genre = genreRepo.findById(genreId).orElseThrow(...);
    album.getGenres().add(genre);
    return albumRepo.save(album);   // INSERT into album_genre
}

public Album removeGenre(Long albumId, Long genreId) {
    Album album = albumRepo.findById(albumId).orElseThrow(...);
    Genre genre = genreRepo.findById(genreId).orElseThrow(...);
    album.getGenres().remove(genre);
    return albumRepo.save(album);   // DELETE from album_genre
}
Copy
These two methods give you CRUD on the join table (add = Create, remove = Delete). Reading the relationship is just a normal GET on the Album.

6️⃣ Controllers (REST endpoints)
Create a controller package. Below is a compact version; you can split each entity into its own controller class if you prefer.

package com.promineotech.musiclibrary.controller;

import com.promineotech.musiclibrary.entity.*;
import com.promineotech.musiclibrary.service.*;
import lombok.RequiredArgsConstructor;
import org.springframework.http.ResponseEntity;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.*;

import java.util.List;

@RestController
@RequestMapping("/api")
@RequiredArgsConstructor
public class MusicController {

    private final ArtistService artistSvc;
    private final AlbumService  albumSvc;
    private final GenreService  genreSvc;

    /* ---------- Artist ---------- */
    @GetMapping("/artists")
    public List<Artist> allArtists() { return artistSvc.findAll(); }

    @PostMapping("/artists")
    public Artist createArtist(@RequestBody Artist a) { return artistSvc.create(a); }

    @GetMapping("/artists/{id}")
    public Artist getArtist(@PathVariable Long id) { return artistSvc.findById(id); }

    @PutMapping("/artists/{id}")
    public Artist updateArtist(@PathVariable Long id, @RequestBody Artist a) { return artistSvc.update(id, a); }

    @DeleteMapping("/artists/{id}")
    public ResponseEntity<Void> deleteArtist(@PathVariable Long id) {
        artistSvc.delete(id);
        return ResponseEntity.noContent().build();
    }

    /* ---------- Album ---------- */
    @GetMapping("/albums")
    public List<Album> allAlbums() { return albumSvc.findAll(); }

    @PostMapping("/albums")
    public Album createAlbum(@RequestBody Album a) { return albumSvc.create(a); }

    @GetMapping("/albums/{id}")
    public Album getAlbum(@PathVariable Long id) { return albumSvc.findById(id); }

    @PutMapping("/albums/{id}")
    public Album updateAlbum(@PathVariable Long id, @RequestBody Album a) { return albumSvc.update(id, a); }

    @DeleteMapping("/albums/{id}")
    public ResponseEntity<Void> deleteAlbum(@PathVariable Long id) {
        albumSvc.delete(id);
        return ResponseEntity.noContent().build();
    }

    /* ---------- Genre ---------- */
    @GetMapping("/genres")
    public List<Genre> allGenres() { return genreSvc.findAll(); }

    @PostMapping("/genres")
    public Genre createGenre(@RequestBody Genre g) { return genreSvc.create(g); }

    @GetMapping("/genres/{id}")
    public Genre getGenre(@PathVariable Long id) { return genreSvc.findById(id); }

    @PutMapping("/genres/{id}")
    public Genre updateGenre(@PathVariable Long id, @RequestBody Genre g) { return genreSvc.update(id, g); }

    @DeleteMapping("/genres/{id}")
    public ResponseEntity<Void> deleteGenre(@PathVariable Long id) {
        genreSvc.delete(id);
        return ResponseEntity.noContent().build();
    }

    /* ---------- Join‑table operations ---------- */
    @PostMapping("/albums/{albumId}/genres/{genreId}")
    public Album addGenreToAlbum(@PathVariable Long albumId, @PathVariable Long genreId) {
        return albumSvc.addGenre(albumId, genreId);
    }

    @DeleteMapping("/albums/{albumId}/genres/{genreId}")
    public Album removeGenreFromAlbum(@PathVariable Long albumId, @PathVariable Long genreId) {
        return albumSvc.removeGenre(albumId, genreId);
    }
}
Copy
Important notes
Jackson infinite‑recursion – Because Artist ⇆ Album ⇆ Genre are bi‑directional, you’ll get a stack overflow when serializing to JSON. Fix it with one of the following (pick one):

// Option A – use Jackson annotations
@JsonManagedReference   // on the parent side
@JsonBackReference      // on the child side
Copy
// Option B – use @JsonIgnore on the back‑reference collection
@JsonIgnore
private Set<Album> albums;
Copy
Validation – Add javax.validation annotations (@NotBlank, @Size, etc.) on DTOs or entity fields and annotate controller parameters with @Valid if you want request‑body validation.

Swagger / OpenAPI – If you want a UI to explore the API, add the SpringDoc dependency (see section 8).

7️⃣ Run the application
Build: mvn clean install (or use Eclipse → Run As → Maven build).

Start: mvn spring-boot:run (or run MusicLibraryApplication as a Java Application).

Check the console – you should see Hibernate DDL statements (because ddl-auto: update).

Test – open Postman (or Swagger UI, see next section) and hit the endpoints, e.g.:

POST http://localhost:8080/api/artists with body
{"name":"DJ Alpha","description":"Electro‑house pioneer"}
Copy
GET http://localhost:8080/api/albums – should return an empty list initially.
Create an Album referencing the Artist ID you just got, then add a Genre, then call
POST http://localhost:8080/api/albums/{albumId}/genres/{genreId} to insert a row into album_genre.
Delete the same URL with DELETE to remove the row (CRUD on the join table).
If everything works, you have satisfied:

One‑to‑many (Artist → Album)
Many‑to‑many (Album ↔ Genre) with explicit add/remove endpoints (CRUD on the join table)
Full CRUD on each entity (Artist, Album, Genre) – at least one entity (all three) has all four operations.
