2. JPA Entity Sketches

// ---------- Artist ----------
@Entity
@Table(name = "artist")
public class Artist {

    @Id @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)
    private Long artistId;

    @Column(nullable = false, unique = true)
    private String name;

    @Column(length = 2000)
    private String bio;

    @OneToMany(mappedBy = "artist",
               cascade = CascadeType.ALL,
               orphanRemoval = true)
    private Set<Album> albums = new HashSet<>();

    // getters / setters / constructors omitted for brevity
}

// ---------- Album ----------
@Entity
@Table(name = "album")
public class Album {

    @Id @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)
    private Long albumId;

    @Column(nullable = false)
    private String title;

    private Integer releaseYear;

    @ManyToOne(fetch = FetchType.LAZY)
    @JoinColumn(name = "artist_id", nullable = false)
    private Artist artist;

    @ManyToMany
    @JoinTable(name = "album_genre",
        joinColumns = @JoinColumn(name = "album_id"),
        inverseJoinColumns = @JoinColumn(name = "genre_id"))
    private Set<Genre> genres = new HashSet<>();

    // getters / setters / constructors omitted
}

// ---------- Genre ----------
@Entity
@Table(name = "genre")
public class Genre {

    @Id @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)
    private Long genreId;

    @Column(nullable = false, unique = true)
    private String name;

    @Column(length = 1000)
    private String description;

    @ManyToMany(mappedBy = "genres")
    private Set<Album> albums = new HashSet<>();

    // getters / setters / constructors omitted
}

The album_genre join table is created automatically because of the @ManyToMany mapping.


-
3. Repository Interfaces (Spring Data)

public interface ArtistRepository extends JpaRepository<Artist, Long> {}

public interface AlbumRepository extends JpaRepository<Album, Long> {}

public interface GenreRepository extends JpaRepository<Genre, Long> {}

No extra repository is needed for the join table – you’ll manipulate the relationship 
through the Album and Genre services.

-

4. Service Layer (high-level responsibilities)
ArtistService: CRUD for artists; when deleting an artist, cascade-delete all its albums 
(thanks to orphanRemoval).
AlbumService: CRUD for albums; methods to addGenre(albumId, genreId), removeGenre(albumId, genreId), 
and replaceGenres(albumId, Set) – these are the CRUD operations on the many-to-many relationship.
GenreService: CRUD for genres; optional helper to list all albums belonging to a genre.

Each service validates existence of foreign keys before performing the operation and 
throws a ResourceNotFoundException (mapped to HTTP 404).

-

5. REST Controllers & Endpoints (Postman-ready): see images
All endpoints return standard JSON payloads and proper HTTP status codes 
(201 Created on POST, 204 No Content on successful DELETE, 404 when a resource isn’t found, etc.).

-

6. Sample Seed Data (5‑10 rows)
You can load this with a simple data.sql file placed in src/main/resources (Spring Boot runs it on startup).

INSERT INTO artist (artist_id, name, bio) VALUES
(1, 'The Beatles', 'Legendary English rock band'),
(2, 'Daft Punk', 'French electronic duo');

INSERT INTO genre (genre_id, name, description) VALUES
(1, 'Rock', 'Guitar-driven popular music'),
(2, 'Pop', 'Catchy mainstream tunes'),
(3, 'Electronic', 'Synthesizers and drum machines');

INSERT INTO album (album_id, title, release_year, artist_id) VALUES
(1, 'Abbey Road', 1969, 1),
(2, 'Revolver', 1966, 1),
(3, 'Discovery', 2001, 2);

-- Join rows (album ↔ genre)
INSERT INTO album_genre (album_id, genre_id) VALUES
(1, 1), (1, 2),          -- Abbey Road is Rock & Pop
(2, 1),                  -- Revolver is Rock
(3, 3);                  -- Discovery is Electronic


That gives you 2 artists, 3 albums, 3 genres, and a handful of join rows,
enough to test every CRUD path in Postman.

-

7.  Testing with Postman / ARC
Import a collection – you can export the table above as a Postman collection (JSON) 
or manually create the requests using the endpoint table.
Run the “Smoke Test” sequence
GET /api/artists → expect 2 items.
POST /api/artists → create a new artist, capture its ID.
POST /api/albums → create an album for that artist.
POST /api/albums/{newAlbumId}/genres/1 → link a genre.
GET /api/albums/{newAlbumId}/genres → verify the link exists.
DELETE /api/albums/{newAlbumId}/genres/1 → remove the link.
DELETE /api/artists/{newArtistId} → cascade delete the album.
All responses should match the expected status codes; 
any failure indicates a missing cascade or a mis-configured mapping.

